This paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it deals with designing a learning algorithm for positive and unlabeled instances. It also involves selecting reliable samples based on fuzziness, which is a common technique used in machine learning. Additionally, the paper may also fall under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it involves designing an algorithm to learn from data. The use of data editing technique to filter out noise points may also suggest that the paper could belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) or natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-categories. Finally, the use of fuzzy logic and the focus on selecting reliable samples may also suggest that the paper could belong to the discrete mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category.
